column21: I want to suggest a better way than 50 tries. Either roll a random index from 0 to N-2 and add 1 if >= the index of your current location; OR iterate over start location and if each entry is a valid target, roll a random number to determine whether to switch to it as the target.

column13: TRANSPORT now tries harder to send you to a different starting location.
column21: Hilarious edge case: the map generator only places 1 Tower of Souls. What happens here in that case?

column13: TRANSPORT now tries harder to send you to a different starting location.
column21:
I actually tried it with 1 Tower, which is how my map generated. It just leaves you in the same place with no lag.
Random index once sounds like it would work, but has the edge case of 1 tower (random index between 0 and -1 will fail). Iterating 0->N would give an increasingly smaller chance of transporting to the later towers, and would fail with the 1 tower edge case.
If you want, I can re-implement it with the random index algorithm that includes a fix for the edge case, but the code as it stands doesn't have a performance hit and seems to function correctly.

column13: TRANSPORT now tries harder to send you to a different starting location.
column21: Actually if you keep rolling progressively smaller chances like !number(0, num_found_so_far) you get the same chance each time. Some other parts of the code use this method but I’m not near my computer to find an example

column13: TRANSPORT now tries harder to send you to a different starting location.
column21: Changed logic. It rolls once, and if it matches the current index then increments by one; if this overflows the array then it goes back to index 0. Also renamed a variable for clarity.

column20:
Per #251.
Summarized:

Added ACTF_VEHICLE_SPEEDS flag. Replaced ACTF_ALWAYS_FAST with this on driving, riding, and piloting. This flag sets a flat number of speed boosts based on the vehicle's speed.
Added speed to vehicles, expressed as a number of boosts from 0-4 (very slow -> very fast). Added saving/loading, OLC, statting, and related infrastructure.
Modified clear_vehicle() to set this value to VSPEED_NORMAL (2) to cause all vehicles to mimic current behavior unless otherwise configured.
